        "text": "From there it has come to considerations whether just the other way round imbalance could not be a condition of stability. According to this, an economic system could only be stable if it either produces too many goods in order to be able to offer something in any case when there is a demand on the market, or if, conversely, it produces too many buyers and too few goods in order to have buyers in any case who, if enough goods are available, will buy them. [[Jänos Kornai]], a Hungarian economist, has developed such anti-equilibrium concepts. One can see that this maps respectively the Western and Eastern economies within the capitalist-socialist controversy: Either goods must be kept scarce and buyers or demand abundant, then you are in the socialist system, or conversely buyers must be scarce and goods abundant, then you are in the capitalist system. In any case, we are dealing here with a version of nonequilibrium theory that differs from classical and neoclassical economics in that it moves stability from equilibrium to disequilibrium."
